The paper deals with game-theoretic models for strategic voting, which falls under the category of computational social choice (cs.GT). The use of best-response heuristics and the analysis of voting equilibria suggest a connection to artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The consideration of different uncertainty levels and simultaneous strategic decisions involves the use of algorithms and data structures (cs.DS). The analysis of regret-minimizing behavior and convergence results suggest a connection to machine learning and statistical inference (cs.SI). Finally, the use of game-theoretic models and convergence analysis also suggests a connection to theoretical machine learning (cs.LG).
